Ideas, in Romer's formulation, really do have consequences. Big ones.", "whotheyare": "Paul Romer's research on catch-up growth in low- and middle-income countries has emphasized the importance of government policies that encourage orderly urban expansion.", "whylisten": "

Paul Romer believes in the power of ideas. He first studied how to speed up the discovery and implementation of new technologies. But to address the big problems we'll face this century -- insecurity, harm to the environment, global poverty -- new technologies will not be enough. We must also speed up the discovery and implementation of new rules, of new ideas about how people interact.

Throughout human history, big improvements in systems of rules took place when new governments entered the scene. In today's world, this process has been largely shut down. To bring it back to life, Romer proposes that we create new cities where people can go to escape from bad rules and opt in to new and better ones. With better rules, people can be safe, self-interest can protect the environment, and investment can bring families all the resources that the modern world has to offer.

Romer took office as the World Bank's Chief Economist and Senior Vice President in October 2016.

aws-transcripts.transcript: take a look at this picture. It poses a very fascinating puzzle for us. These African students are doing their homework under streetlights at the airport in the capital city because they don't have any electricity at home. Now I haven't met these particular students, but I've met students likethe Um, Let's just pick one, for example, the one in the green shirt. Let's give him a name to Nelson. I'll bet Nelson has a cell phone. So here's the puzzle. Why is it that Nelson has access to a cutting edge technology like cell phone but doesn't have access to a 100 year old technology for generating electric light in the home? Now, in a word, the answer is rules. Bad rules can prevent the kind of win win solution that's available when people can bring new technologies in and make them available to someone like Wilson. What kinds of rules The electric company in this nation operates under rule, which says that it has to sell electricity at a very low subsidized price. In fact, a price that solo it loses money on every unit that it sells. So it has neither the resource is nor the incentive tow hook up many other users. The president wanted to change this rule.
